4/27/26

* Based on some thoughts I had while walking back to my apartment from the grocery store, knowing that I would soon move to the East Coast, not to return for several years.

The frigid air stung my eyes
as if to call me weak
for the tears that dance but dare not chance
to crawl across my cheek,

for the salty silver slivers
that never burned my eyes,
these wounds, disgraced, upon my face,
their pupils my disguise.

And then a question blinks alight
within my rampant mind,
of thoughts unsaid and books unread,
my duty in a bind,

and for a while I drift in dream
of sultry summer Sundays,
but here, instead, I break my bread
on cold and callous Mondays.

For these dry days, someday too soon,
will be the "good 'ol days",
when autumn moons sang out their tunes
in amber-crimson haze,

and then I'll see my present self
as "me, when I was younger";
nostalgic trips evoke my thirst,
for future years I hunger.